\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Stochastic Progenitors in Esophageal Epithelium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The esophageal lining in adult mice is composed of a stratified epithelium
 (Figure), which rapidly regenerates during adulthood to act as a protective
 lining.
 Similar to inter-follicular epidermis (IFE), it is composed of multiple
 layers of keratinocytes, sitting atop a membrane that separates it from
 the rest of the mucosa.
 As in IFE, proliferation is confined to the basal layer of cells; upon
 differentiation, the cells stratify from the basal layer, lose their nucleus
 and much cellular machinery to turn into large, flat cells which are no
 longer transcriptionally active.
 Unlike epidermis, the esophageal epithelium (EE) lacks any gross anatomical
 features such as hair follicles, instead being composed of an spatially
 and temporally homogeneous population of keratinocytes undergoing continuous
 division and loss.
 It is thus uniquely suited as a clean environment in which to dissect the
 functional behaviour of cells with regards to their fate choice, via lineage
 tracing by inducible genetic labelling techniques.
 Specifically, we use genetically modified mice which carry an Enhanced
 Yellow Flourescent Protein (EYFP) gene, muted by a stop-cassette; upon
 treatment with tamoxifen the gene is activated by deletion of the stop
 cassette, leading to the production of EYFP in that cell and all its progeny.
 By using a very low does of tamoxifen, it is possible to reduce the rate
 of induction such that EYFP-positive cells are widely spaced, and thus
 at some later time each cluster of EYFP-positive progeny (clonal cluster,
 or clone) can be assumed to have come from a single progenitor (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-pictures"

\end_inset

).
 It is then possible to measure by counting the distribution of clone sizes,
 both as a univariate distribution in basal cell count (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-basal-raw"

\end_inset

), or a two-dimensionally joint distribution in basal and suprabasal cell
 counts (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-joint-data"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename oes-basal-pictures.jpg
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:oes-pictures"

\end_inset

Protocol: Clonal labeling was induced in genetically engineered mice and
 analyzed at intervals from 3 days to 1 year (triangles).
 Images are rendered confocal z stacks of the basal layer showing typical
 clones at times indicated.
 Enhanced yellow fluorescent protein (EYFP), yellow; DAPI, blue.
 Scale bars, 10 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the work of [Clayton and Doupé], such techniques were used to show that
 the textbook [cite?] model of epithelial proliferative units supported
 by a single long-lived, asymmetrically dividing stem cell is at odds with
 the observed basal clone size distribution, and that a stochastic model
 of progenitors dividing both symmetrically and asymmetrically is capable
 of reproducing the experimental data.
 We will engage in a similar analysis, and go further by establishing a
 quantitative framework that allows precision measurement of relevant quantities
 such as rate of turnover and proportions of progenitor fate choice.
 We then use the method to analyse the action of a drug (all-
\emph on
trans
\emph default
 retinoic acid) by quantitatively describing its action on the fate outcome
 of the progenitors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of great biological significance, but relatively independent of the analysis
 of clone size distributions, is the discovery that there are no long-lived
 slow-cycling stem cells in the EE at all.
 As such, the progenitors which we analyse in detail are also capable of
 repair, by switching to a different pattern of behaviour.
 The reader interested in these issues may find a discussion in [Doupe 2012].
 This chapter draws significantly on that publication, especially the supplement
ary therein; the experimental work was performed by DPD, MPA and AR, project
 planning by PHJ, thorough discussion with AMK, and data analysis by GZ
 and BDS.
 PHJ wrote the main text of Ref [cite], but section 2.2 is the authorship
 of BDS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will set out in detail the experimental evidence in support of the esophageal
 progenitor (EP) cell model, how the parameters of this model are constrained
 by the experimental data, and how the model can be challenged experimentally
 by drug treatment.
 In section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:model"

\end_inset

 we will describe how the experimental data identifies the dynamics of a
 single progenitor cell population allowing us to formulate a simple model
 of EE turnover.
 In section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:quant"

\end_inset

 we will use the clonal fate data to fit the parameters of the modelling
 scheme.
 Finally, in section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:chall"

\end_inset

, we will challenge the model by considering the effects of drug delivery
 on tissue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Clonal analysis: defining the model of EP cell dynamics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Scaling and equipotency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename basal-raw-gen.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:oes-basal-raw"

\end_inset


\series bold
Main figure
\series default
: clone size distribution (basal cells/clone) in a total of 1784 clones,
 each point represents one clone.
 
\series bold
Insets:
\series default
 (top left and right) average basal clone size and average density of clones
 in the basal layer, observed values (orange) with error bars (mean ± SEM),
 blue curves show predictions of model (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-normal-model"

\end_inset

).
 (middle left) average percentage of labelled basal cells at indicated time
 points (orange), error bars indicate mean ± SEM, green line and shading
 show average and SEM across all time points.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To isolate and quantify the behavior of proliferating cells, we scored the
 number of basal cells in clones containing two or more cells (i.e.
 clones in which a proliferative cell was labeled at the start of the experiment
) from 3 days to one year post-induction, by confocal imaging of esophageal
 wholemounts (fig).
 Previously, it has been shown that in a similar homeostatic stratified
 squamous epithelium, interfollicular epidermis, a simple statistical characteri
zation can be used to both establish the equipotency of a self-renewing
 cell population, and elucidate the pattern of cell fate (cite 18, 19).
 In particular, if self-renewal involves the stochastic loss and replacement
 of such progenitors, clones derived from these cells will undergo a process
 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutral drift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in which ongoing clonal loss is compensated by the expansion of adjacent
 clones.
 However complex is the underlying dynamics, such processes lead inexorably
 to the long-term scaling of the surviving clone size distribution, in which
 the chance of finding a clone with a size larger than some multiple of
 the average remains constant over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename basal-scaling.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:oes-basal-scaling"

\end_inset

Cumulative clone size distribution shows convergence onto scaling behaviour
 at late times.
 The raw basal layer clone size distribution in (fig) is reproduced here
 as the cumulative clone size distribution, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}(t)$
\end_inset

, plotted as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 divided by the average clone size for each timepoint.
 The cumulative distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}(t)$
\end_inset

 represents the probability of finding a surviving clone with a basal layer
 size larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 At times of 3 months or more post-induction, the data sets converge onto
 each other, a manifestation of long-term scaling behaviour.
 Combined with the observed homeostatic nature of the turnover, such scaling
 behaviour shows that the self-renewing progenitor cells function as a functiona
lly equivalent population.
 The black curve denotes an exponential cumulative clone size distribution;
 the long-term behaviour predicted for any strategy involving population
 asymmetric self-renewal including the model discussed here (1-2).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applied to the current dataset, the convergence of the basal layer clone
 size distribution onto a scaling form (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-basal-scaling"

\end_inset

) both confirms the functional equivalence of the self-renewing progenitor
 cell population, and shows that the balance between their proliferation
 and differentiation is achieved on a population basis, and not at the level
 of individual cell divisions, i.e., in the course of turnover, some cells
 may undergo terminal division leading to loss while others may undergo
 symmetric duplication.
 Indeed, such behavior is consistent with the observed heterogeneity in
 the clonal composition at short times, which reveals that, soon after induction
, all possible permutations of two-cell clones can be found (i.e.
 two basal cells, one basal and one suprabasal, and two suprabasal cells).
 The same degree of heterogeneity is apparent in larger clones (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-basal-raw"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taken together, the results above suggest that, as in interfollicular epidermis,
 EE is maintained by a single cycling progenitor cell population in which
 cell division can lead to all three possible fate outcomes; two daughters
 that go on to divide, two cells that exit cycle and then stratify out of
 the basal layer, or one daughter that goes on to divide and one that differenti
ates (cite 18, 19).
 To assess the validity of this model, and to quantify the respective rates
 and probabilities, we must turn now to a more detailed analysis of the
 short-time data, prior to scaling, where signatures of the detailed dynamics
 can be elucidated.
 To prepare for this analysis, we must embed the progenitor cell dynamics
 into a parameterization that includes the stratification and loss of terminally
 differentiated cells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parameterizing EP dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be concrete, we will suppose that the basal layer comprises a single
 population of cycling esophageal progenitor cells (with proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

), and their differentiating progeny (with proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\rho$
\end_inset

), which remain in the basal layer without dividing until they stratify.
 If we assume that the progenitors divide with an average rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, and the differentiating cells stratify at an average rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, to achieve homeostasis, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\rho=(1-\rho)\gamma$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the rate at which differentiated cells are generated in the basal layer
 must be perfectly matched by the rate at which they stratify into the suprabasa
l cell layer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To further specify the model, we must also define the distribution of cell
 cycle and stratification times.
 Here, for simplicity, we will suppose that division and stratification
 are both uncorrelated between successive events leading, in both cases,
 to an exponential (Poisson) time distribution, with averages set by the
 rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 While this assumption is surely unsafe (after all, cell division must be
 accompanied by a small refractory period before further division is possible),
 any degree of synchrony in the cell cycle or stratification timings will
 be rapidly erased from the clonal record over the timecourse.
 In particular, we expect features due to potential synchrony to be lost
 within experimental error bars after ca.
 1--2 rounds of division (cite 20).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alongside the division and stratification rates, we must further specify
 the probabilities for the respective fate outcomes following division.
 Since both the labeled cell number and their composition is found to be
 conserved over the time course, any process of cell division must be consistent
 with homeostatic turnover.
 Moreover, since, through scaling, EPs are seen to function as an equipotent
 cell population, we will therefore suppose that proliferation and differentiati
on is finely balanced so that, with probability, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, EP division results in two dividing cells, with probability, 
\begin_inset Formula $1-2r$
\end_inset

, one dividing and one non-dividing basal later cell, and with probability,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, two non-dividing basal layer cells.
 Although we cannot rule out a small contribution arising from perpendicular
 cell divisions resulting in the placement of one of the daughters directly
 into the suprabasal layer, given such divisions are observed to be rare,
 the effect of such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

orientationally asymmetric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 divisions would again be impossible to resolve.
 Similarly, we will neglect apoptosis, which was found to be negligible
 in the basal layer (Fig.
 S4E).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, the time-evolution of the basal layer population, along with
 the clonal fate data, is therefore fully characterized by three adjustable
 parameters, the division rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, the stratification rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and the fraction of divisions that lead to symmetrical fate, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The progenitor cell fraction is then fixed by the rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\gamma/(\lambda+\gamma)$
\end_inset

.
 To fully characterize the behavior of the 
\emph on
total
\emph default
 clone size, including suprabasal as well as basal cells, we must include
 a further parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, which defines the average rate at which suprabasal cells are shed from
 the tissue (once again, we will suppose for simplicity that the corresponding
 distribution of shedding times is Poisson).
 Fortunately, this additional parameter can be related directly to the division
 and stratification rates through the ratio of nucleated suprabasal to basal
 layer cells, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, which can be measured directly.
 Then, since the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flux
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of differentiated cells stratifying from the basal layer must be perfectly
 compensated by the flux of differentiated cells that are shed, we must
 have 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mu=\rho\lambda=\gamma\lambda/(\gamma+\lambda)$
\end_inset

, thereby providing a relation linking 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taken together, the EP cell model dynamics can be cast as a critical (i.e.
 balanced) continuous time Markovian branching process, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
{\rm EP}\stackrel{{\displaystyle {\lambda}}}{\longrightarrow} & \left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
{\rm EP}+{\rm EP} & {\rm Pr.}\ r\\
{\rm EP}+{\rm T}_{{\rm B}} & {\rm Pr.}\ 1-2r\\
{\rm T}_{{\rm B}}+{\rm T}_{{\rm B}} & {\rm Pr.}\ r
\end{array}\right.\\
{\rm T}_{{\rm B}}\stackrel{{\displaystyle {\gamma}}}{\longrightarrow} & {\rm T}_{{\rm S}},\\
{\rm T}_{{\rm S}}\stackrel{{\displaystyle {\mu}}}{\longrightarrow} & \textrm{loss},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{EP}$
\end_inset

 represents the progenitor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{B/S}}$
\end_inset

 differentiated cells in the basal/suprabasal layer, and the rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 are defined above.
 As discussed above, we suppose that EP cell fate follows a pattern of intrinsic
 or cell-autonomous regulation in which the fate outcome following division
 is uncorrelated with the behavior of neighboring cells.
 In previous studies, we have shown that, in the two-dimensional geometry
 pertinent to EE, the long-term clonal dynamics is largely insensitive to
 this choice (30).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This completes the specification of the cellular dynamics as a generalized
 branching-type process.
 In principle, we could further refine the modeling scheme to include aspects
 of the spatial regulation.
 However, our aim here is to establish and challenge the simplest model
 which is consistent with the observed range of clonal fate data.
 Indeed, we will find that, by itself, this model provides a faithful descriptio
n of the cellular dynamics over the timecourse of the experiment.
 To assess the integrity of the model, and to fit the three adjustable parameter
s, we will make use of a Bayesian approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Clonal analysis: quantitative modeling
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:quant"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Scaling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the EP cell paradigm, following induction, a differentiated
 basal or suprabasal cell would progressively stratify, lose its cell nucleus
 and be shed, providing only a transient contribution to the clonal dynamics.
 By contrast, a clone derived from an EP cell would progressively undergo
 chance expansion or contraction according to the fate choice of the constituent
 cells.
 As tissue turns over, the gradual extinction of some clones due to chance
 commitment to terminal differentiation will be perfectly compensated by
 the expansion of other clones.
 Analysis of the branching process shows that, over time, neutral drift
 dynamics leads to a progressive (linear) increase in the average size of
 the surviving clones, while the surviving fraction falls proportionally
 such that the total density of labeled cells remains constant (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-basal-raw"

\end_inset

, inset middle left) (18).
 In this regime, the basal layer clone size distribution acquires a scaling
 behavior (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-basal-scaling"

\end_inset

) described above.
 In particular, the chance of finding a clone with more than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 basal layer cells, takes the form of an exponential 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp[-n/\langle n(t)\rangle]$
\end_inset

 where, according to the parameters of the model, the average basal layer
 clone size (i.e.
 the average size of the clone 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

footprint
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the basal layer) is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle n(t)\rangle\simeq t/\tau$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\tau=\rho/r\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the long-term scaling behavior provides the means to extract the
 characteristic timescale 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (see below), the rapid convergence to this regime does not allow the individual
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 to be inferred reliably from the basal layer clone size distribution alone.
 Therefore, to properly validate the model, and effect a reliable fit of
 the parameters, we consider the full range of clonal fate data, short-term
 and long-term, basal and suprabasal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parameter estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data itself is acquired in the form of a set of frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $D=\left\{ f_{bn}(t)\right\} $
\end_inset

 describing the number of observations of clones with 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 basal cells and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 suprabasal cells at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

; an example is Fig.
 S6B.
 The stochastic nature of our model will predict probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}(t)$
\end_inset

 for a single cell to turn into a clone at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 basal and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 suprabasal cells, based on the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 One might approach the fit with a least-squares method to optimize the
 parameters.
 However, as a significant portion of our data lies in the tails with large
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, where the counts are small, we would have to employ complex methods such
 as ad-hoc binning or continuity corrections.
 As such, we have elected to use a more Bayesian approach, which allows
 us to analyze the experiment with no manipulation of the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fit the model to the range of experimental data, we implement a basic
 algorithm involving Bayes' theorem for updating prior probabilities in
 the presence of data.
 More precisely, the probability that the observed clonal fate data 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is described by the model is specified by the proportionality, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(\lambda,r,\rho|D\right)\propto P\left(D|\lambda,r,\rho\right)P\left(\lambda,r,\rho\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the posterior distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(D|\lambda,r,\rho)$
\end_inset

 denotes the probability of obtaining the data 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 given the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, multiplied by the likelihood that the parameters are given by those same
 values.
 The constant of proportionality may be calculated 
\emph on
a posteriori
\emph default
 by imposing the normalisation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}\! d\lambda\int_{0}^{1}\! d\rho\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}}\! dr\, P\left(\lambda,r,\rho|D\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 In our case, the posterior distributions will turn out to be approximately
 Gaussian, so we may characterize the distribution by its first two moments
 and treat them as a point estimate for the parameters, and a credible interval
 covering approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $68\%$
\end_inset

 (using one standard deviation) or 
\begin_inset Formula $95\%$
\end_inset

 (using two).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Bayes' equation above, it is apparent that we need to specify a prior
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\lambda,r,\rho\right)$
\end_inset

 and a likelihood function 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(D\middle|\lambda,r,\rho\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We chose the maximum entropy prior as we have no further cogent information,
 which corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 uniform on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 uniform on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\frac{1}{2}\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 log-uniform.
 Crucially, since we have sufficient data, the likelihood function is sharply
 peaked and only significant on a small support, and thus the posterior
 distribution is dominated by the likelihood function, and so any reasonable
 prior (one which does not fluctuate strongly over that narrow support)
 would give quantitatively similar results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning to the likelihood function, since each observed clone is independent,
 it is a multinomial distribution with a countable number of outcomes: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(D\middle|\lambda,r,\rho\right)=\prod_{t}\frac{\left[\sum_{bn}f_{bn}(t)\right]!}{\prod_{bn}\left[f_{bn}(t)!\right]}\prod_{bn}\left[p_{bn}(t)\right]^{f_{bn}(t)},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}(t)$
\end_inset

 denote the expected probabilities that a clone contains 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 basal cells and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 suprabasal cells at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 post-induction.
 In the following, we will suppress the time index 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 for notational concision where it is considered unambiguous.
 To eliminate potential ambiguities due to uncertain induction frequencies
 of the two cell types, we conditioned the data on having at least two cells,
 which removes the events where a differentiated cell is induced.
 Moreover, to focus on a defined population, we further consider only clones
 which retain at least one basal layer cell.
 Thus we consider the probabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{bn}\mapsto\tilde{p}_{bn}=\begin{cases}
0 & b=0\textrm{ or }b+n<2,\\
\frac{p_{bn}}{1-p_{10}-\sum_{n}p_{0n}} & \textrm{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}$
\end_inset

, we consider the more fundamental distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{lmn}$
\end_inset

 describing the (unconditioned) probability of finding a clone with 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 progenitors, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 differentiated basal layer cells and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 suprabasal cells.
 From these probabilities we can determine 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}$
\end_inset

 through the relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}=\sum_{l+m=b}p_{lmn}$
\end_inset

.
 The probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{lmn}$
\end_inset

 obey a continuous time Markov process, with the time-evolution given by
 the Master equation, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}p_{lmn} & =\lambda\left[r(l-1)p_{(l-1)mn}+(1-2r)lp_{l(m-1)n}+r(l+1)p_{(l+1)(m-2)n}-lp_{lmn}\right]\\
 & +\gamma\left[(m+1)p_{l(m+1)(n-1)}-mp_{lmn}\right]-\mu np_{lmn}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with the initial conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{lmn}=\delta_{l1}\delta_{m0}\delta_{n0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although this is a straightforward set of coupled differential equations,
 direct numerical solution is prohibitively computationally expensive because
 each element is coupled to all the others: attempts to truncate the 
\begin_inset Formula $lmn$
\end_inset

-space causes errors that are hard to control.
 Instead, to develop the computational scheme, it is helpful to package
 the equations into the form of a generating function, 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,y,z,t)=\sum_{lmn}p_{lmn}(t)x^{l}y^{m}z^{n}$
\end_inset

, which obeys the differential equation, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial G}{\partial t} & =\lambda\left[rx^{2}+(1-2r)xy+ry^{2}-x\right]\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}+\gamma\left(z-y\right)\frac{\partial G}{\partial y}+\mu(1-z)\frac{\partial G}{\partial z},\\
 & =\lambda\left[f_{x}(x,y,z)-x\right]\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}+\gamma\left[f_{y}(x,y,z)-y\right]\frac{\partial G}{\partial y}+\mu\left[f_{z}(x,y,z)-z\right]\frac{\partial G}{\partial z}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,y,z,t=0)=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{x}(x,y,z) & =rx^{2}+(1-2r)xy+ry^{2},\\
f_{y}(x,y,z) & =z,\\
f_{z}(x,y,z) & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be recognised as the probability generating functions for individual
 divisions of each cell type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The partial differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 may be solved by the method of characteristics.
 Introducing the auxiliary equations, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}F_{v}(\mathbf{v},t)=a_{v}\left[f_{v}\left(F_{x},F_{y},F_{z}\right)-v\right]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 ranges over the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y,z\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{v}$
\end_inset

 ranges over 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda,\gamma,\mu\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{v}(\mathbf{v},t=0)$
\end_inset

 ranges over 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y,z\}$
\end_inset

, we can write the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,y,z,t)=F_{x}(x,y,z,t)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we can recognize the auxiliary function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{v}$
\end_inset

 as the probability generating functions for the clone size distribution
 starting with a cell of type 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{lmn}$
\end_inset

 may be extracted from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by complex analysis.
 Indeed, it is possible to directly extract 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}$
\end_inset

 by considering 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,x,z,t)$
\end_inset

.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(x,y,t)=G(x,x,y,t)=\sum_{bn}p_{bn}(t)x^{b}y^{n},
\]

\end_inset

we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is analytic in both 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 on the complex unit disc 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|,|y|\le1$
\end_inset

, and so there are no poles within it.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 to be an anticlockwise contour around the unit circle, we can recover 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}$
\end_inset

 by considering residues at zero: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{bn}(t)=\left(\frac{1}{2\pi i}\right)^{2}\oint_{\mathcal{C}}dx\oint_{\mathcal{C}}dy\frac{H(x,y,t)}{x^{b+1}y^{n+1}}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that, up to a minus sign, it is just a multi-dimensional inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

-transform.
 The integral can be approached by a sum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{bn}(t)=\lim_{M\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{j=1}^{M}\sum_{k=1}^{M}H\left(e^{2\pi ij/M},e^{2\pi ik/M},t\right)e^{-2\pi ijb/M}e^{-2\pi ikn/M}
\]

\end_inset

the truncation of which at finite 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 approximates the integral and is in the form of a two-dimensional discrete
 Fourier transform.
 This allows the use of industrial Fast Fourier Transforms to evaluate all
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{bn}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 being a power of two simultaneously.
 We use adaptive oversampling to estimate the error in the truncation, and
 use it to bound the errors.
 This gives a robust black box algorithm which gives point estimates and
 credible intervals for arbitrary clonal data sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before finally carrying out the parameter estimation, it is important to
 confirm that the degree of inter-mouse variation is sufficiently small
 to justify collating data from different mice.
 For this purpose, we made use of the long-term scaling behaviour of the
 clone size distribution.
 Although, generically, the dynamics of the basal layer cells depends independen
tly on the three adjustable parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, in the scaling limit, the basal layer clone size depends only on the only
 on the combination, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\tau=r\lambda/\rho$
\end_inset

, a measure of the rate of progenitor cell loss and replacement.
 As a result, this parameter can be estimated with a smaller uncertainty,
 allowing it to be inferred on a mouse by mouse basis for each timepoint.
 Inferring this parameter from the basal layer clone size distribution,
 as well as the total clone size at shorter times, the comparison shown
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:oes-intermouse"

\end_inset

 reveal that, although there is some degree of inter-mouse variation, the
 amalgamation of data from different mice at the same timepoint can be justified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
