\begin_layout Subsection
Single cell clones
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the development of the EP model relied upon the observation of
 long-term scaling behavior of the basal layer clone size distribution which
 suggested that tissue maintenance involves only a single equipotent progenitor
 cell population.
 However, by focusing on clones with a total size greater than one, we eliminate
d the potential signature of a second very slow-cycling or quiescent cell
 population.
 Although the existence of such a population in EE was ruled out by the
 H2B-GFP assay, with the predictions of the EP model, we can do back and
 question whether the dynamics of the single-cell clones are consistent
 with the ansatz of the modeling scheme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since, for times in greatly in excess of the cell stratification time, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\gamma$
\end_inset

, differentiated cells labeled at induction will have been lost from the
 basal layer, we can use the long-term evolution of the single-cell basal
 clones to challenge the predicted model dynamics.
 Once again, the results, shown in Fig.
 S13, reveal an excellent agreement between theory and experiment over the
 year long timecourse.
 In particular, we can conclude that the persistence of single-cell clones
 merely reflects the set of clones which, by chance, have expanded and the
 sister cells have been shed leaving behind a single labeled cell.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename singles.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:oes-single-cell"

\end_inset

There is a very slow decay of the relative frequency of clones consisting
 of a single basal cell.
 Nevertheless, this is well accounted for by the model (Fig.
 2F).
 Here we plot the observed relative frequency in orange, and in blue the
 model prediction (with 95% likelihood intervals arising from finite number
 of clones counted).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have shown that there is a population of progenitors in EE which maintains
 the tissue, which is modelled by a simple stochastic branching process.
 The progenitors divide at a constant rate and chose one of three fates
 with fixed probabilities; differentiated cells stratify and eventually
 shed.
 The model contains four parameters: the EP cell division rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, the ratio of symmetric to asymmetric cell divisions controlled by the
 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, the stratification rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and the loss rate of cells from tissue 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The latter is fixed by the ratio of basal to suprabasal cells, which may
 be accurately measured; the other three were measured from observed clone
 size distributions.
 Moreover, we have shown that this model can capture the effect of atRA
 treatment through a straightforward adjustment of the average EP cell division
 rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Theorems on Super-critical Branching Processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When cancer cell lines are cultured, it is sometimes observed that all cells
 remain in cell cycle (according to biochemical markers).
 It therefore seems reasonable to model the cells as independent and identical,
 which has a natural expression in the theory of super-critical branching
 processes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Athreya2004"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, as the cells proliferate rapidly, it is possible to obtain
 some fairly large amount of statistics regarding the clone size distribution.
 It is well-known that the limit distribution depends on the lifetime distributi
on of the particles, i.e.
 the cell cycle distribution.
 We therefore seek to infer the cell cycle distribution from the measurable
 clone size distribution.
 Concretely, we attempt to invert the relationship between the cell cycle
 distribution and the clone size distribution, and investigate its stability
 and (un)suitability as a practical procedure.
 Along the way we find that not all distributions can arise as the limiting
 distribution of a super-critical branching process, and we conjecture and
 prove some properties of them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter was inspired by conversations with the Jones team, who provided
 the initial data for this theoretical detour.
 It is unfortunate that ultimately the results were not sufficiently useful
 to be biologically relevant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The inversion formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an equipotent population of cells which divide independently.
 This may be modelled as a branching process, defined by specifying the
 cell cycle distribution be 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 and the branching outcomes of each division, which we package into a generating
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)=\sum_{k}p_{k}s^{k}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the probability for the cell to divide into 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 daughters.
 We will restrict ourselves to biologically feasible processes, in particular
 we will require all moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to exist.
 Furthermore, we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, as it simplifies the consideration by avoiding total death of the clone;
 for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 we can construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star}$
\end_inset

 of equal order such that no death occurs, with the only difference being
 the existence of terminal clones (see appendix
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:condition-survival"

\end_inset

).
 We also exclude certain pathological behaviours from consideration, such
 as the possibility for a clone to reach infinite size in finite time, which
 excludes in particular the existence of a Dirac delta spike at zero in
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 We consider in particular the 
\emph on
super-critical
\emph default
 process, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(1)>1$
\end_inset

 and the expected number of cells diverges exponentially at a rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left[f,g\right]$
\end_inset

 (the Malthusian parameter of the process), defined by the (only) root of
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-\alpha y}g(y)\, dy=1.
\]

\end_inset

 In the limit of infinite time, the distribution (normalised to unit mean)
 of the total number of cells converges to a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

, whose characteristic function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)=\mathbb{E}\left[e^{iuW}\right]$
\end_inset

 is the unique solution (amongst distributions with unit mean) of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(u)=\int_{0}^{\infty}f\left[\phi\left(ue^{-\alpha y}\right)\right]g(y)\, dy.\label{eq:forwards-eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Notice that since the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 sets a scale for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, we may remove it by scaling 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with no change to the limiting behaviour.
 Therefore without loss of generality we shall set 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can consider equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 as a family of non-linear transform on the space of distributions over
 the positive reals, indexed by the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 It We note two properties (see appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:injective-continuity"

\end_inset

) in particular: it is continuous (in 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

-norm), and injective (for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, up to scaling of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

).
 In particular, this implies that if we know the branching of cells (which
 for biological applications we can obtain by experiment), it is in principle
 possible to undo the transform and infer the cell cycle length from experimenta
l clone size distributions.
 However, as we will show below, this turn out to be overly optimistic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In passing we note that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

, treated as an iterative procedure, is stable and convergent.
 However, numerical implementation will have to deal with the inevitable
 deviation from the manifold of proper characteristic functions.
 In practice, we find that it is sufficient to use a cubic spline approximation
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, and clamp the boundary at the origin: 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(0)=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{\prime}(0)=i$
\end_inset

.
 With an initial guess corresponding to an exponential distribution for
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, this reliably converges to a distribution, although the mean often deviates
 from unity by a few percent.
 The convergence is fast enough to be interactive and allow numerical experiment
s, but only just.
 We show some examples in appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:forward-examples"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To invert the transformation, defining 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=\phi\left(e^{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(t)=\int_{0}^{\infty}f\left[h\left(t-y\right)\right]g(y)\, dy,
\]

\end_inset

which is simply a convolution.
 Proceeding formally, we may take Fourier transforms and obtain the 
\emph on
Klein inversion formula
\emph default

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The formula was independently, and to the knowledge of the author prior,
 discovered by AM Klein, 
\emph on
private correspondence
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{\tilde{h}(\omega)}{\widetilde{f\odot h}(\omega)},\label{eq:backward-eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\odot h$
\end_inset

 is the composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 followed by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{t\rightarrow-\infty}h(t)=\phi(0)=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is not integrable.
 Furthermore, since 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

 considered as a distribution on the entire real line almost certainly has
 discontinuities in its derivatives at the origin, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)$
\end_inset

 will have algebraic decay for large 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=O\left(e^{-ct}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, for some finite 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{h}$
\end_inset

 will only converge and thus be defined on the strip 
\begin_inset Formula $-c<\Im\left(\omega\right)<0$
\end_inset

 (the strip will be as least as wide for 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f\odot h}$
\end_inset

).
 Thus for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 to be well-defined, we require that the quotient in the inversion formula
 be analytically extended to include the real line, and give a characteristic
 function on it; in addition, it must be entirely analytic in the lower
 half-plane in order for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to be causal, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t<0$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore we are led to study what exactly is the image of the transform
 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 (equivalently the domain of the Klein formula).
 We can show than the tail of 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

 is bounded from above by any power-law decay and from below by an exponential,
 and conjecture that it is in fact exactly exponential (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:moment-theorems"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Directly applying the Klein formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:examples"

\end_inset

), we can reproduce the known results for the exponential (Markovian) process,
 and the discrete time process.
 In addition, we can concretely invert the gamma distribution.
 However, more generally, although formally we can invert distributions
 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=p(W)e^{-\lambda W}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is some polynomial, generically they do not yield proper distributions
 upon inversion.
 We conjecture that in the space of distributions, at a generic point in
 the image of the forwards transforms, almost all directions (i.e.
 perturbations) lead off the manifold; but nevertheless, there is a countable
 number of perturbations which remain on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Practically, for application to experimental data, the outlook is pessimistic
 for two reasons.
 One is that because the transform in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 is continuous, there is not a sharply optimal choice for an inverse that
 optimises some cost function (likelihood, for instance).
 In particular, numerical experiments show that changes to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 which do not significantly change extreme behaviours tends to have negligible
 effect on the outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Second is that although the transform is injective, meaning that it is
 invertible, it depends on having access to the limiting distribution.
 For interesting problems, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 having power law tails, a real experiment necessarily will fail to probe
 the tail structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generically (and realistically), we might have multi-type processes.
 There we encounter the problem that it would be necessary to have access
 to the limit distributions starting from all the different cell types,
 which may present a complete barrier to experiments.
 It is an open question however, about whether one can approximate a multi-type
 process with a single-type process, by appropriately choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, we find that as a practical procedure, the inversion formula
 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backward-eq"

\end_inset

) is not practical for biological applications.
 Nevertheless, it is possible to use it to find some novel pairs of limiting
 distributions and cell cycle lengths, which would otherwise necessitate
 solving a non-linear integral equation (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:condition-survival"

\end_inset

Conditioning on survival
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit, the probability for extinction is given by the smallest positive
 root of 
\begin_inset Formula $q=f(q)$
\end_inset

.
 We can define a new process with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\star}(s)=\frac{f\left[\left(1-q\right)s+q\right]-q}{1-q}
\]

\end_inset

which will yield the a limit distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\star}(W)=(1-q)H(W)+q\delta(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Note in particular that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of the same order as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:forward-examples"

\end_inset

Examples of limiting distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we consider a simple binary fission 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)=s^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributed cell cycles
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{\beta^{\beta}t^{\beta-1}e^{-\beta t}}{\Gamma(\beta)}.
\]

\end_inset

The limiting distributions (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:g-gamma-limits"

\end_inset

) are remarkably close to being 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributed also, but not quite (inset).
 As we show in appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:examples"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributions are legitimate limiting distributions, but to a slightly
 different cell cycle distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/genneth/Documents/super-limit/gamma-set.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:g-gamma-limits"

\end_inset

Limit distributions for binary fission with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributed cell cycle lengths.
 Inset shows that the limit distributions are very close 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributions, but not exactly.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the transform in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 is continuous, the limit distribution will not change qualitatively for
 moderate changes to the cell cycle distribution.
 In particular, the biologically relevant example of a mono-modal distribution
 with an initial refractory period is sufficiently close to give very similar
 limit distributions.
 In any case, since the right tail is always exponential (appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:moment-theorems"

\end_inset

), the only qualitative change possible is the behaviour near the origin,
 i.e.
 increase the proportion of clones smaller than the average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we may consider a process where the division of each cell can produce
 a large number of progeny relative to the average.
 Specifically, consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(s)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{s^{k}}{2^{k}}=\frac{s}{s-2}.
\]

\end_inset

 For the Markovian process it is possible 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "III.8, theorem 3"
key "Athreya2004"

\end_inset

 to analytically obtain the limit distribution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(W)=\frac{1}{2}\left[-1+\frac{2e^{-W/4}}{\sqrt{\pi}\sqrt{W}}+\mathrm{erf}\left(\frac{\sqrt{W}}{2}\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

which has a weak divergence at the origin.
 More intuitively, if we consider the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log W$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
J(s)=H\left(e^{s}\right)e^{s} & =\frac{e^{\frac{s}{2}-\frac{e^{s}}{4}}}{\sqrt{\pi}}-\frac{1}{2}e^{s}\mathrm{erfc}\left(\frac{e^{s/2}}{2}\right)\\
 & \sim\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}e^{s/2}\textrm{, }s\rightarrow-\infty,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we see that it still decays exponentially.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, we can simply have some cells which divide very slowly.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:g-power-limits"

\end_inset

 shows the limit distributions for binary fission with the family 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(t)=\frac{\mathrm{sinc}\left(\frac{n}{\pi}\right)}{1+\left(t-\frac{1}{2}\right)^{n}}\Theta\left(t-\frac{1}{2}\right),\ n\ge2.\label{eq:power-law-g}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As can be seen in the inset, the corresponding distribution in 
\begin_inset Formula $\log W$
\end_inset

 has a power-law tail for small 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, implying a divergence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(W)\approx\frac{C}{W\log^{n}W},\ W\rightarrow0.
\]

\end_inset

Notice however, that the local minimum in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 becomes closer to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, and the divergence at the origin become more narrow.
 If we impose an upper-end cut-off to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

, then the divergence is removed, without significant changes to the rest
 of the curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/genneth/Documents/super-limit/power-set-W.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


