\end_inset

Limit distributions for binary fission power-law tailed cell cycles.
 Left shows the divergence which occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $W\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 Right shows the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log W$
\end_inset

, which has power-law tails for large negative 
\begin_inset Formula $\log W$
\end_inset

 (inset).
 The very right tail, and the left tail of the inset shows numerical noise;
 the distributions are uniformly continuous.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:injective-continuity"

\end_inset

Injectiveness and continuity of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Injectiveness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that two different 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 give the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 upon transform with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

.
 We may assume without loss of generality that their respective Malthusian
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are equal and unity (if they are not we can simply scale the cell cycle
 distributions).
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\infty}f\left[\phi\left(e^{t-y}\right)\right]\left[g_{1}\left(y\right)-g_{2}\left(y\right)\right]dy=0,
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Using the convolution theorem we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f\odot\phi}\left(\omega\right)\left[\tilde{g}_{1}\left(\omega\right)-\tilde{g}_{2}\left(\omega\right)\right]=0
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Im\left\{ \omega\right\} >0$
\end_inset

, obtaining that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are analytic, regular and equal on an open strip.
 Thus as characteristic functions they are equal, and the original functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are equal as distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Continuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having established injectiveness, and since Fourier transforms are continuous,
 it is sufficient to establish the continuity of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:backward-eq"

\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=h_{0}(t)+\delta h(t)$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left[h(t)\right]=f\left[h_{0}(t)\right]+\delta h\left(t\right)f^{\prime}\left[h_{0}\left(t\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le h_{0}(t)\le1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(s)$
\end_inset

 is bounded within 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le s\le1$
\end_inset

 so define 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\sup_{t}f^{\prime}\left[h_{0}\left(t\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Taking norms of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:backward-eq"

\end_inset

, we can straightforwardly compute: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\Vert \widetilde{\delta g}\right\Vert  & =\frac{\left\Vert \tilde{h}_{0}\right\Vert +\left\Vert \widetilde{\delta h}\right\Vert }{\left\Vert \widetilde{f\odot h_{0}}\right\Vert +\left\Vert \widetilde{\delta h\, f^{\prime}\left[h_{0}\right]}\right\Vert }-\left\Vert \tilde{g}_{0}\right\Vert \\
 & =\left\Vert \widetilde{\delta h}\right\Vert \left\Vert \widetilde{f\odot h_{0}}\right\Vert -\left\Vert \tilde{h}_{0}\right\Vert \left\Vert \widetilde{\delta h\, f^{\prime}\left[h_{0}\right]}\right\Vert +O\left[\left\Vert \widetilde{\delta^{2}h}\right\Vert \right]\\
 & \le\left\Vert \widetilde{\delta h}\right\Vert \left\{ \left\Vert \widetilde{f\odot h_{0}}\right\Vert +A\left\Vert \tilde{h}_{0}\right\Vert \right\} +O\left[\left\Vert \widetilde{\delta^{2}h}\right\Vert \right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:moment-theorems"

\end_inset

Of moments and tails
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 we get (via Fa
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
`a
\end_layout

\end_inset

 di Bruno's formula):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi^{(n)}(u)=\int_{0}^{\infty}\left\{ \sum_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{n!}{k_{1}!\cdots k_{n}!}f^{(k)}\left[\phi\left(ue^{-y}\right)\right]\left[\frac{\phi^{(1)}\left(ue^{-y}\right)e^{-y}}{1!}\right]^{k_{1}}\cdots\left[\frac{\phi^{(n)}\left(ue^{-y}\right)e^{-ny}}{n!}\right]^{k_{n}}\right\} g(y)\, dy
\]

\end_inset

where the summation runs over all partitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}+2k_{2}+\cdots+nk_{n}=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=k_{1}+\cdots+k_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Recognising these as moments (up to factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 which may be removed without loss of generality by picking the right boundary
 conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) gives (using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}=\phi(0)=1$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{n}=\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{n!}{k_{1}!\cdots k_{n}!}f^{(k)}\left(1\right)\left(\frac{M_{1}}{1!}\right)^{k_{1}}\cdots\left(\frac{M_{n}}{n!}\right)^{k_{n}}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy.\label{eq:moment-recursion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we assumed that all moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exist, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(k)}(1)$
\end_inset

 will also exist.
 Noticing that there is only one partition with 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}=1$
\end_inset

, we can move that term to the left hand side and we get for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge2$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{n}\left[1-\int_{0}^{\infty}f^{\prime}(1)e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy\right]=C\left[M_{1},\ldots,M_{n-1}\right],
\]

\end_inset

where the right hand side only depends on the lower moments, and in particular
 is finite if all the lower moments are finite.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\int_{0}^{\infty}f^{\prime}(1)e^{-y}g(y)\, dy>\int_{0}^{\infty}f^{\prime}(1)e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy
\]

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 is finite, by induction all moments exist.
 Thus, applying Chebychev's inequality we get 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)\in o\left(W^{-\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 We conjecture that it is actually exponentially bounded, and show this
 below for binary fission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now outline an argument that the tails are also bounded from below by
 an exponential.
 First, generally if two non-negative variables 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}$
\end_inset

 have moments obeying
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[W_{1}^{n}\right]\ge\mathbb{E}\left[W_{2}^{n}\right]
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w>w_{0}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}\left[W_{1}>w\right]\ge\mathbb{P}\left[W_{2}>w\right].
\]

\end_inset

To see this, consider the contrapositive, which is that if the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[W_{1}>w\right]<\mathbb{P}\left[W_{2}>w\right]$
\end_inset

 is unbounded, then for at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[W_{1}^{n}\right]<\mathbb{E}\left[W_{2}^{n}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 We then check two cases: (a) if it there exist arbitrarily large 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[W_{1}>w\right]>\mathbb{P}\left[W_{2}>w\right]$
\end_inset

 then it would be a contradiction for the moments to be dominated 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, if the moments 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n}\right]\in n\log n+\Theta(n)$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 then the tail 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]$
\end_inset

 is exponential, in some sense.
 In particular, existing work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Abate1996"

\end_inset

 suggests that if the limits 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{n}=\frac{n\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n-1}\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n}\right]}\rightarrow\eta
\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{n}=\frac{\eta_{n}^{n}\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n}\right]}{n!}\rightarrow A
\]

\end_inset

 exist, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{w\rightarrow\infty}e^{\eta w}\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]=A.
\]

\end_inset

 Finally, we consider equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:moment-recursion"

\end_inset

 and drop all terms higher than quadratic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{M_{n}}{n!}\ge\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\frac{M_{k}M_{n-k}}{k!(n-k)!}\frac{f^{\prime\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}{1-f^{\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}\label{eq:moments-lower-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which follows as each term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:moment-recursion"

\end_inset

 is positive.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(n)=M_{n}/n!$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi(n)\ge\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\xi(k)\xi(n-k)K_{n},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
K_{n} & =\frac{f^{\prime\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}{1-f^{\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}\\
 & >\frac{f^{\prime\prime}(1)}{1-f^{\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-2y}g(y)\, dy}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy\\
 & \ge C\eta^{-n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

.
 Using the equality we can convert this into a lower bound 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{n}\ge\frac{n!}{C\eta^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

which by the above gives an exponential tail.
 Thus, we conclude that the tail of a limit distribution is exponentially
 bounded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of binary fission, we can improve the upper bound slightly.
 In particular, the equality in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:moments-lower-bound"

\end_inset

 applies.
 An upper bound on the moments is then given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{K_{2}M_{n}}{n!}\le\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\frac{K_{2}M_{k}}{k!}\frac{K_{2}M_{n-k}}{(n-k)!}.
\]

\end_inset

with equality for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\le2$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{2}=\frac{2\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-2y}g(y)\, dy}{1-2\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-2y}g(y)\, dy}.
\]

\end_inset

We obtain an upper bound in terms of the Catalan numbers
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{K_{2}M_{n}}{n!}\le\frac{K_{2}^{n}(2n-2)!}{(n-1)!n!}
\]

\end_inset

Then applying the moments bound
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Philips1995"

\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]=\inf_{n}\frac{M_{n}}{w^{n}}\le\inf_{n}\frac{K_{2}^{n-1}(2n-2)!}{(n-1)!w^{n}},
\]

\end_inset

which for large 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]=O\left(\frac{1}{w}\right)e^{-\frac{w}{4K_{2}}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we note that removing the assumption that all moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exist will remove the upper bound but not the exponential lower bound.
 Furthermore, if the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is infinite, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 will be as well, suggesting a tail 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)\approx W^{-k-1}$
\end_inset

; indeed, the moment will diverge at finite times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:examples"

\end_inset

Applications of the Klein inversion formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Delta distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=\delta(W-1)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)=e^{iu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=e^{ie^{t}}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{h}(\omega)=e^{\pi\omega/2}\Gamma\left(-i\omega\right)$
\end_inset

, defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\Im(\omega)<1$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(s)=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}p_{k}s^{k}
\]

\end_inset

 (notice that we do not have a constant term), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f\odot h}(\omega)=e^{\pi\omega/2}\Gamma\left(-i\omega\right)\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}p_{k}k^{i\omega}
\]

\end_inset

defined on the same strip.
 The quotient is then well defined:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}p_{k}k^{i\omega}}.
\]

\end_inset

If only one 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero (and therefore equal to one), we would have a well-defined
 distribution
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\delta(t-\ln k),
\]

\end_inset

which reproduces the trivial result that a discrete time Markovian process
 with fixed outcomes in each division necessarily leads to a Dirac distribution
 as the limit.
 For a more generic 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 it does not lead to a probability distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Exponential tailed distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As conjectured, the tail of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is always exponential.
 With the integral above we can consider the very general class
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(W)=\sum_{k}a_{k}\frac{\lambda^{k+1}}{\Gamma(k+1)}W^{k}e^{-\lambda W}
\]

\end_inset

where normalisation requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}a_{k}=1$
\end_inset

 and unity mean requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}a_{k}(k+1)/\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, though as we shall see the latter will be automatically enforced.
 The characteristic function is very helpfully just a sum
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(u)=\sum_{k}a_{k}\left(1-\frac{iu}{\lambda}\right)^{-k-1}.
\]

\end_inset

Importantly, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\odot\phi$
\end_inset

 has the same structure, composed of a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-iu/\lambda)^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we only have to consider a single integral (convergent on 
\begin_inset Formula $-k-1<\Im\{\omega\}<0$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{i\omega t}\left(1-\frac{ie^{t}}{\lambda}\right)^{-k-1}dt\\
= & \lambda^{i\omega}\int_{0}^{\infty}z^{i\omega-1}(1-iz)^{-k-1}dz\\
= & \lambda^{i\omega}e^{-\pi\omega/2}\frac{\Gamma\left(1+k-i\omega\right)\Gamma\left(i\omega\right)}{\Gamma(1+k)}\\
= & \lambda^{i\omega}e^{-\pi\omega/2}\Gamma(1-i\omega)\Gamma\left(i\omega\right)\frac{\left(1-i\omega\right)_{k}}{\Gamma(1+k)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z\right)_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the Pochhammer symbol.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:backward-eq"

\end_inset

, upon taking the quotient all but the last factor above cancel.
 Define the auxiliary polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)=\sum_{k}a_{k}z^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(z)=\frac{1}{z}f\left[zP(z)\right]$
\end_inset

 and a transform on polynomials defined by being linear and acts on each
 monomial as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{z^{k}}\Longrightarrow\frac{(1+z)_{k}}{\Gamma(k+1)}.
\]

\end_inset

Then by linearity we immediately get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{\widehat{P}(-i\omega)}{\widehat{Q}(-i\omega)}.
\]

\end_inset

Notice that the formula above is completely independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

; the correct one such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

 has mean of unity will be chose.
 We can find 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 by applying the Heaviside formula to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(iz)$
\end_inset

 (treating it as an inverse Laplace transform), and generically it will
 be a sum of exponentials (possibly with complex exponents, but always occurring
 in conjugate pairs), determined by the locations of zeros of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that whilst 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}(z)$
\end_inset

 cannot have any zeros on the positive real line, generically there may
 be zeros on the right half plane.
 Below, we will try and give some simple cases where this can be done and
 it yields proper cell cycle distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest case is 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=e^{-W}$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(z)=\frac{1}{z}f(z)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{1}{\sum_{k}p_{k}(1-i\omega)_{k-1}/\Gamma(k)}.
\]

\end_inset

If only one 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=(k-1)e^{-(k-1)t}\left(e^{t}-1\right)^{k-2}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular this reproduces the result that for binary fission (
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

) the Markovian process (
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)=e^{-t}$
\end_inset

) gives an exponential distribution in the limit.
 Biologically cells can only divide into two, so we can consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=(1-r)z+rz^{2}.$
\end_inset

 In that case, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{1}{r}e^{-t/r},
\]

\end_inset

 which is again Markovian, and, in hindsight obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another simple case is when 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distribution; in that case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)=z^{\beta-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(z)=\frac{1}{z}f\left(\beta^{\beta}z^{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{g}(\omega) & =\frac{(1-i\omega)_{\beta-1}/\Gamma(\beta)}{\sum_{k}p_{k}(1-i\omega)_{k\beta-1}/\Gamma(k\beta)}\\
 & =\left[\sum_{k}p_{k}\frac{(\beta-i\omega)_{(k-1)\beta}}{(\beta)_{(k-1)\beta}}\right]^{-1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If only one 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero then the poles are simple and line on the positive imaginary
 axis, and furthermore 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 is positive:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{\Gamma(k\beta)}{\Gamma(\beta)\Gamma\left[(k-1)\beta\right]}e^{-(k\beta-1)t}\left(e^{t}-1\right)^{(k-1)\beta-1}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that this reproduces, in appropriate limits, the results above for
 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=e^{-W}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=\delta(W-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:H-gamma"

\end_inset

 shows some examples from this family.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/genneth/Documents/super-limit/gamma-inverse.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:H-gamma"

\end_inset

Cell cycle distributions that gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributions with shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 as limit distributions, when each cell divides exactly into 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 at the end of its life.
 In blue we show the variation as 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2,3,\ldots,50$
\end_inset

 for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=3$
\end_inset

.
 The two red series show variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1,\ldots,9$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=20$
\end_inset

.
 In thick black, we show the intersections 
\begin_inset Formula $k=4,\ \beta=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=20,\ \beta=3$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 the distributions approach a Dirac delta distribution, with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the above is well-defined for all positive real 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, not only positive integers.
 In addition, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

, it produces a family of distributions which when scaled to have unit mean
 is well-approximated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{\beta}e^{-\beta t}t^{\beta-1}/\Gamma(\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 Lastly, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/(k-1)$
\end_inset

, we get an exponential distribution for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, thus solving the Markovian problem for branching with a single 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generically, it becomes very difficult to find the conditions such
 that the Klein formula is well-defined.
 Consider even the restricted case that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=(1-r)z+rz^{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 a generic biologically sensible branching process, starting with a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{g}\left(\omega\right)=\left[(1-r)+r\frac{\left(\beta-i\omega\right)_{\beta}}{\left(\beta\right)_{\beta}}\right]^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset

Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{6e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(5+\sqrt{25-\frac{24}{r}}\right)t}\left(-1+e^{\sqrt{25-\frac{24}{r}}t}\right)}{\sqrt{r(-24+25r)}}
\]

\end_inset

which is only positive everywhere if 
\begin_inset Formula $r>24/25$
\end_inset

, in which case all exponents are real.
 However, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=3$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{60\left[\omega_{1}\left(e^{t\omega_{2}}-e^{t\omega_{3}}\right)+\omega_{2}\left(e^{t\omega_{3}}-e^{t\omega_{1}}\right)+\omega_{3}\left(e^{t\omega_{1}}-e^{t\omega_{2}}\right)\right]}{r\left(\omega_{1}-\omega_{2}\right)\left(\omega_{2}-\omega_{3}\right)\left(\omega_{3}-\omega_{1}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1,2,3}$
\end_inset

 are the three roots to the cubic 
\begin_inset Formula $60+47rz+12rz^{2}+rz^{3}=0$
\end_inset

.
 All three roots have negative real parts for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gtrsim0.106383$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 is not positive for most of that.
 Indeed, only for 
\begin_inset Formula $r>\frac{90\left(270-\sqrt{3}\right)}{24299}\approx0.993626$
\end_inset

 are all three roots real.
 Numerically, it seems that only if all three roots are real is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 well-defined.
 By similar arguments, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=4$
\end_inset

 we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $r>\frac{840}{841}$
\end_inset

; and for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gtrsim0.999906$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The example above required that the poles of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 lay only on the imaginary axis, but this is not necessary.
 Consider binary fission, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z^{2}$
\end_inset

, and a multi-modal 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)=r+(1-r)z^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(z)$
\end_inset

 is of order 7.
 The roots are all real for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\apprle9.164\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset

 and five real roots for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\apprle0.07036$
\end_inset

.
 However, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:multi-modal"

\end_inset

 shows, there exist well-behaved solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\apprle0.35$
\end_inset

, which can be interestingly multi-modal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/genneth/Documents/super-limit/multi-modal.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:multi-modal"

\end_inset

Main figure shows the cell cycle distribution which gives the limit distribution
 in the inset.
 Blue is for 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=\left[r+(1-r)z^{3}W^{3}\lambda^{4}/\Gamma(4)\right]e^{-\lambda W}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int W\, H(W)\, dW=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0.35$
\end_inset

.
 Green is a comparison with the power-law tailed distribution from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:power-law-g"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2.1$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $r\apprge0.35$
\end_inset

 the dip in 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 becomes pronounced enough that it become negative.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 is well-defined, but for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 it is not, even though 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1$
\end_inset

 it is well-defined.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Stochastic Fate Choice in Cultured Rat Retinal Progenitors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central question of developmental biology is how do cells organise their
 divisions to achieve the same body plan reproducibly.
 One could imagine that each cell is pre-programmed with the instructions
 (and classical lineage tracing experiments in 
\emph on
C.
 elegans
\emph default
 suggests that this does occur [cite]), or alternatively there is some complex
 emergent organisation which only manifests within the right environment
 (?? shows the importance of cell-cell interactions for spermatogenesis).
 Here we study rat retinal progenitors from day 20 
\emph on
in vitro
\emph default
; these cells are late in the developmental process, and nearing complete
 diffenentiation.
 Earlier work [Cayouette] had established that even under culture conditions
 retinal progenitors cells (RPCs) will generate the correct proportions
 of retinal cell types, even while each individual RPC generates a heterogeneous
 collection of cells; this raises the possibility that there is indeed a
 great deal of intrinsic pre-programming, but expressed as a stochastic
 procedure which averages over a population to give the correct outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, we focus on an experiment which tracks by time-lapse microscopy
 cultured RPCs, from which detailed lineage trees may be reconstructed,
 showing the exact time of divisions and fate outcomes.
 We show that even though the pattern of divisions seem very complex, there
 is a simple stochastic model which is consistent with the data.
 This draws heavily on the work in [cite]; experimental work was carried
 out by FLAFG, manuscript was written by MC, analysis by GZ and BDS, with
 discussions with WAH, FC and JAC.
 In what follows we will elide the exact experimental procedures, and refer
 the reader to the published work [cite].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experimental results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To study retinal lineages, we cultured E20 rat RPCs at clonal density and
 recorded their development over time using long-term time-lapse microscopy.
 Over a period of more than 2 years, we followed the fate of 2347 RPCs.
 Of these, 856 were excluded from further analysis because the RPC either
 died (6.3%), moved away from the field of view (2.7%), touched another cell
 that was not part of the clone (6.5%), or immediately differentiated without
 dividing (21%).
 As a result, we recovered a total of 1491 RPCs that divided at least once
 to generate clones containing two cells or more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the 1491 RPCs, 1211 were recorded to have undergone a terminal division
 that generated two differentiating daughters, but were not further analyzed
 in terms of cell type composition.
 Of the remaining 280 RPCs that divided more than once, the lineage trees
 of 129 could be reconstructed (all reconstructed lineages leading to clones
 of three or more cells are shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-raw"

\end_inset

), whereas the remaining clones had cells that were lost during the fixation
 and immunostaining process, or the outcome of at least one mitosis could
 not be resolved, most often owing to cells moving on top of each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the successfully reconstructed lineages, there were 465 differentiated
 cells, three of which had an unidentified fate (0.6%), and in the remaining
 cells we found 341 RPh (73.8%), 59 Bi (12.8%), 49 Am (10.6%) and 13 Mu (2.8%).
 These proportions are similar to those obtained after labeling RPCs at
 postnatal day (P) 0 with retroviral vectors in the mouse retina (Turner
 et al., 1990).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the reconstructed lineages vary widely in size and composition,
 and there is no clear order in which cell types are generated.
 In particular, almost all orderings of cell types occur, suggesting that
 the order of retinal cell type production is not strictly encoded in each
 lineage, at least not from E20 onwards in culture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename retinalLineageData1.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename retinalLineageData2.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename retinalLineageData3.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename retinalLineageData4.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename retinalLineageData5.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:rat-raw"

\end_inset

The full dataset of all 129 reconstructed lineages in this study.
 Different cell types are color-coded, as indicated.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stochastic progenitors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the reconstructed lineage data, we first asked how E20 RPCs achieve
 the required balance between proliferation and differentiation.
 We analyzed the different modes of cell division observed in the overall
 population.
 For the ensemble of clones with three or more cells, for which the lineage
 trees were fully reconstructed, the first division must inevitably involve
 the survival of at least one progenitor.
 Therefore, to obtain an unbiased statistical measure of the modes of cell
 division, we examined the lineage trees of the clones with three or more
 cells after their first division.
 Out of 199 divisions recorded, 44 (22.1%) were self- renewing divisions
 that produced an RPC and a differentiating daughter (P/D divisions), whereas
 144 (72.4%) were terminal, giving rise to two differentiating daughter cells
 (D/D divisions).
 Such terminal divisions, although symmetric in the sense that both daughters
 exit the cell cycle, could also be symmetric or asymmetric in the sense
 that the daughter cells may be of the same or different types, respectively.
 To avoid confusion, we shall generally refer to all terminal divisions
 as D/D divisions, regardless of whether the two daughter cells adopt the
 same or different fates.
 Finally, only 11 divisions (5.5%) were found to generate two RPCs (P/P divisions
).
 Since the P/P mode of division accounts for only a small fraction, these
 results indicate that differentiative (D/D) divisions, and to a lesser
 extent self- renewing (P/D) divisions, are the major source of neurogenesis
 and gliogenesis in the perinatal retina, at least in culture.
 Although these figures point unambiguously to the predominance of D/D and
 P/D divisions at this stage of retinogenesis, they leave open the question
 of whether the balance of these division modes changes significantly over
 the timecourse of the experiment.
 To investigate this, we compared the second divisions of each lineage tree
 with those of the third and beyond.
 Of the 131 second divisions, 95 were D/D (72.5±7.4%), 31 were P/D (23.6±4.3%)
 and five were P/P (3.8±1.7%); errors are estimates based on Poisson statistics
 for the counts, i.e.
 (count±count)/total counts.
 This leaves 68 third and beyond divisions, of which 49 were D/D (72.1±10.3%),
 13 were P/D (19.1±5.3%) and six were P/P (8.7±3.6%).
 The difference between the second and third divisions remains within the
 error bars, indicating that over the timecourse of the experiment the ratio
 of D/D, P/D and P/P divisions remains roughly constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The similarity in the relative division ratios between one generation and
 the next suggests that the balance between proliferation and differentiation
 of a RPC is not influenced by the fate of its parent.
 In other words, the division mode of a given RPC (P/P, P/D or D/D) is unpredict
able and, in this sense, stochastic.
 To test this possibility directly, we compared the chance of finding a
 clone of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in the experimental dataset with that predicted by a model in which RPCs
 divide with a fixed probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{PP}=0.055$
\end_inset

 of adopting the P/P cell fate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{PD}=0.221$
\end_inset

 of adopting the P/D cell fate and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{DD}=0.724$
\end_inset

 of adopting the D/D cell fate (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-clone-size"

\end_inset

).
 Strikingly, the results of a Monte Carlo simulation show an excellent agreement
 with the experimental data.
 Moreover, for the same number of clones with three or more cells (129),
 the model predicts an approximately normal distribution for the total number
 of cells across all clones, with an average of 487 and a standard deviation
 of 22.
 This is again consistent with the 465 observed in the experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename F2.large.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	width 65col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:rat-clone-size"

\end_inset

The observed clone size distribution is reproduced by a stochastic model.
 The data points (blue) show the size distribution associated with the 129
 clones with three or more cells.
 If we assume that the balance between proliferation and differentiation
 is determined stochastically, with RPCs dividing with a fixed probability
\begin_inset Formula $P_{PP}=0.055$
\end_inset

 of adopting the P/P cell fate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{PD}=0.221$
\end_inset

 of adopting the P/D cell fate and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{DD}=0.724$
\end_inset

 of adopting D/D cell fate, we obtain the clone size distribution given
 by the red curve.
 The error bars on the theoretical curve denote 95% confidence intervals
 and are a result of the finite sample size.
 Since the probability of adopting the P/P cell fate is small, the size
 distribution is close to exponential, reflecting the fact that the majority
 of clones can be described by a sequence of asymmetric P/D divisions terminatin
g in a D/D division.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results suggest that, at least from E20 and over the timecourse of
 the experiment in vitro, the mode of division of RPCs is stochastic with
 biased probabilities that remain approximately fixed.
 Our previous findings that the size distribution of clones that develop
 in clonal-density cultures is very similar to that of clones that develop
 
\emph on
ex vivo
\emph default
 in retinal explants (Cayouette et al., 2003) suggest that this is not a
 pathology associated with culture conditions.
 In addition, because the RPCs are cultured at clonal density, these results
 suggest that biased probabilities do not depend on specific environmental
 cues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Independence of division and fate choice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next considered whether the time that an RPC spends in the cell cycle
 correlates with cell fate choice.
 We directly measured the cell cycle time of RPCs generating all observed
 combinations of daughter cell pairs by counting the elapsed time between
 the mitosis that produced these cell pairs and the previous one.
 We found no significant difference in cell cycle time of divisions producing
 any of the combinations observed (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-cycle-fate-and-dist"

\end_inset

, left), indicating that cell cycle time does not correlate with any particular
 cell fate decision.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename cycleLengthvsFate.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename cycleLengthHist.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:rat-cycle-fate-and-dist"

\end_inset


\series bold
Left
\series default
: average cell cycle time (mean + population s.d.) of RPCs generating all
 the different combinations of daughter cell pairs observed in this study.
 A, amacrine; B, bipolar; M, Müller; P, progenitor cell; R, rod photoreceptor.
 
\series bold
Right
\series default
: observed cell cycle time distribution (bars) together with a log-normal
 fit (line).
 The mean is 56.0 hours and population s.d.
 is 18.9 hours.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Grouping the data from all cell divisions, independent of fate, we found
 that the cell cycle time was variable within the RPC population, with an
 average of 56.0 hours and a population standard deviation of 18.9 hours.
 The distribution of cell cycles were well approximated by a log-normal
 distribution (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-cycle-fate-and-dist"

\end_inset

, right).
 Also, upon comparing the cell cycle times of any consecutive divisions
 (
\begin_inset Formula $n=61$
\end_inset

), we found no evidence of correlation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-cycle-correlations"

\end_inset

, left).
 However, when we measured the difference in cell cycle times of all the
 daughter cells of P/P divisions (n=21), we found a standard deviation of
 17 hours, significantly smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\times19$
\end_inset

 hours, where 19 hours is the standard deviation of all cell cycle times,
 which would be expected if their division times were uncorrelated.
 This result suggests a degree of synchrony in the timing of division of
 sister RPCs that might contribute to the general timing of retinogenesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results suggested that RPCs do not depend on mechanisms that count
 cell cycle time or the number of divisions to regulate lineage termination.
 By refining the stochastic model associated with the modes of division
 to include a log-normal spectrum of division times (consistent with the
 experimental data), a Monte Carlo simulation shows lineage termination
 times that agree with the overall distribution of termination times obtained
 experimentally (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-cycle-correlations"

\end_inset

, right).
 Together, these results indicate that the timing of lineage termination,
 and thus the overall size of the retina, may be explained simply as the
 result of a combination of stochastic fate decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename divisionSynchrony.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename finishTimesHist.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:rat-cycle-correlations"

\end_inset


\series bold
Left
\series default
: cell cycle times of daughter RPCs plotted against the cell cycle times
 of their mothers reveals no discernable correlation.
 
\series bold
Right
\series default
: The data (bars) show the measured distribution of lineage termination
 times.
 The line shows the predicted distribution of lineage termination times
 for a stochastic model in which the ratios of proliferation and differentiation
 are the same as that defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-clone-size"

\end_inset

, and the distribution of cell cycle times is taken to be log-normal with
 parameters chosen to fit the experimental data in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-cycle-fate-and-dist"

\end_inset

.
 The curve is obtained from a Monte Carlo simulation.
 This comparison provides a sensitive test of the stochastic model, as deviation
s from it are magnified through repeated application.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Almost stochastic cell fate specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous experiments have shown that rod photoreceptors represent 73% of
 all cells in the mouse retina in vivo (Young, 1985), and, similarly, 73.8%
 of all cells produced in the reconstructed lineages were RPh.
 How is such an imbalance of cell type production achieved? It could be
 that multipotent RPCs are largely biased toward producing photoreceptor
 cells at each division.
 Alternatively, it could be that a subset of RPCs becomes committed at some
 point in their lineage to generate exclusively RPh cells, thereby greatly
 increasing the number of RPh cells that can be produced from the same RPC
 pool size.
 Although differences may exist between in vivo and in vitro lineage progression
, the continuous observation of RPC lineages performed in this study allowed
 us to begin to address this problem directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To benchmark the experimental data, we used a model in which both the balance
 between proliferation and differentiation, and the differentiated cell
 type, were chosen at random, with probabilities fixed by the measured average
 of each cell type produced in the clones (i.e.
 the probability that a differentiated cell adopts an RPh fate is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{RPh}=0.738$
\end_inset

, etc.), independent of the fate of its sister, parent or any other cell
 in its lineage.
 Then, to seek evidence for lineage specification, we looked for the simplest
 statistical measure focusing on the correlation of cell fate between consecutiv
e generations of cells.
 Specifically, we explored the correlation between the fates of two consecutive
 lineage-related divisions.
 From a total of 201 qualifying divisions from within the 129 clones, the
 number that generated a given cell fate versus the fate of the sister of
 the parent cell is shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:rat-comparison"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename comparisonTable.pdf
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:rat-comparison"

\end_inset

Each entry displays three quantities for a given triplet of cells generated
 by two consecutive lineage-related divisions.
 The number in a large font denotes the observed frequency of the event.
 The superscript represents the prediction made by a stochastic model in
 which the relative division probabilities leading to proliferation and
 differentiation are set by the parameters shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:rat-clone-size"

\end_inset

, and the relative probabilities of the differentiated cell types is specified
 at random with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{RPh}=0.738$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{Bi}=0.128$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{Am}=0.106$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{Mu}=0.028$
\end_inset

, corresponding to the observed frequencies of the population.
 The subscript indicates the quality of the agreement between the experiment
 and the stochastic model, expressed as the number of experiments (each
 involving 201 aunt/niece triplets) one would expect to perform before seeing
 a statistical fluctuation of this magnitude or greater.
 This figure should be compared with the total number of entries (75) –
 much greater than this is a sign of a genuine outlier.
 Outliers that stand at three and four standard deviations are light and
 dark red, respectively.
 For example, the entry at (RPh, RPCRPh) represents events involving two
 consecutive P/D divisions in which both differentiated progeny adopted
 the RPh cell fate.
 Out of the 201 entries, from the table, we find that such an event occurred
 24 times.
 This compares to the 19.4 average predicted by the stochastic model.
 From the subscripted number, we see that one would expect to see a departure
 from the theoretical prediction of this magnitude or larger in one out
 of four experiments owing to statistical fluctuations, i.e.
 the observed data are entirely compatible with the statistical model.
 By contrast, if we look at the entry (Bi, AmBi), we expect to see an average
 of 0.4 events out of 201, whereas the data show six.
 Such a fluctuation would arise in typically only one out of 4.6 million
 experiments, i.e.
 the observed data are clearly incompatible with the statistical model as
 defined.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the raw experimental data several features emerged.
 First, there were a number of entries for which no examples were found.
 Second, several of the entries were large, including the putative RPh lineage
 (RPh, RPhRPh) and (RPh, RPCRPh).
 However, by themselves, neither of these observations provides conclusive
 evidence for recurring lineage patterns.
 Since the data were acquired from only a limited number of clones, if certain
 lineage combinations were rare we might indeed expect to record no examples
 in the limited data set.
 Moreover, if cell fate choice were stochastic, but heavily biased toward
 RPh fate, we might find large entries in a seemingly RPh-specific lineage
 that derived simply by chance and not from early lineage commitment.
 Thus, to calibrate the data we used the stochastic model as a benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Table 2, we also show the expected number of entries for an experiment
 with the same number, 201, of qualifying cell divisions if cell fate outcome
 were random.
 In addition, we have included the number of experiments (each with 201
 qualifying cell divisions) that we would expect to have to perform to find
 at least one experiment with a statistical fluctuation that was equal to,
 or larger than, the actual measured experimental value.
 If this number is greatly in excess of the 75 possible fate outcomes in
 the table, we can consider the entry as an outlier, seemingly inconsistent
 with the random hypothesis.
 If, by contrast, it lies within 75, any departure of the experimental value
 from the expected result can be explained simply as a fluctuation associated
 with small-number statistics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this analysis, we noticed, for example, that the large entry for (RPh,
 RPCRPh) lies well within the expected range for the random model, along
 with the vast majority of other entries, consistent with such combinations
 being produced stochastically.
 However, from the 75 entries, five outliers were identified, which stand
 at three or more standard deviations from the expected average: (RPC, RPCRPC);
 (RPh, AmAm); (RPC, AmBi); (RPC, BiMu); and (Bi, AmBi).
 Such outliers should appear at most only once per 370 entries.
 Moreover, the (Bi, AmBi) entry lies beyond five standard deviations and
 indeed would only be expected to appear around once in 4.6 million experiments.
 Clearly, these cannot be explained simply as a number fluctuation, and
 although the chronology of cell type production might somewhat influence
 lineage selection, these results suggest that, in addition to stochastic
 mechanisms, specific recurring lineages or lineage priming may play a part
 in retinogenesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We studied rat retinal progenitors in culture, by reconstructing complete
 lineage trees from time-lapsed imaging.
 We find a great deal of heterogeneity in both size and composition of the
 resulting lineages, but which can be almost entirely explained by a simple
 model of time-invariant progenitors which undergo a stochastic process
 of division and fate specification.
 Whilst there were outliers in the fate outcomes observed, the results suggest
 that a great deal of the development is regulated intrinsically, but not
 stereotypically.
 Nevertheless, we are cautious in interpreting the results, as they are
 in the context of cultured cells at the late end of development.
 In the next chapter, we go on to a 
\emph on
in vivo
\emph default
 system which encompasses a much greater range of the developmental program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
How Stochastic Progenitors Build an Invariant Zebrafish Retina
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the last chapter, we saw that retinal progenitor cells (RPCs) in culture
 can be modelled by a simple stochastic process of independent and time-invarian
t progenitors with fixed proportions for fate outcomes.
 Aside from the occasional correlation in lineage trees which are statistically
 significantly deviant from the model, a more serious problem is that the
 system is 
\emph on
in vitro
\emph default
, with no real tissue being built and so no potential for cell-cell interactions
 to become manifest.
 In this chapter, we move to consider a system in live zebrafish embryos,
 which via a battery of genetic labelling techniques, also allow different
 ways to trace lineage trading detail for data volume .
 However, given the complexity of the system and difficulty of obtaining
 sufficient data, the model will be necessary more descriptive than prescriptive.
 In particular, we have only found a possible model of relative simplicity,
 rather than the unique and most simple model possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter draws significantly from [cite]; the experimental work was
 primary by JH, and ADA, the manuscript by WAH and data analysis by GZ and
 BDS and discussions with MC.
 However, we have elided detailed discussion of the experimental methods
 and their validation (which in itself was a year-long project for the experimen
talists), and focus on the clonal analysis.
 We again refer the interested reader to the published work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The developing zebrafish retina in space and time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The retina is a pseudo-stratified epithelium, with progenitors being elongated
 with processes that attached each cell to a basal membrane.
 The fully developed retina has distinct layers of cell types (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-retina-anatomy"

\end_inset

), but progenitors can, and tend to, move apically before dividing, and
 the daughters will move basally to settle into the correct layer.
 Over a short period of time (20--72 hpf) the retina grows by a factor of
 approximately 12 in cell number, by both expansion in volume and increase
 in density of cells.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename zf-anatomy-schematic.png
	width 30text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename zf-saggital-sections.png
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:zf-retina-anatomy"

\end_inset


\series bold
Left
\series default
: schematic of the developed retina; the ciliary margin zone (CMZ) contains
 adult stem cells which continue to grow the eye as the fish grows through
 adulthood.
 
\series bold
Right
\series default
: Representative images of the sagittal sections and the created retina
 surfaces (inserts) at distinct developmental stages; note the distinct
 asymmetry present at the intermediate phase (24--32 hpf) across the ventral-dor
sal plane.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From previous works (Hu and Easter, 1999; Neumann and Nuesslein-Volhard,
 2000), it is known that a wave of differentiation progresses from central
 to peripheral and nasal to temporal around the retina.
 Given the asymmetry observed early (24 hpf) in the retina (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-retina-anatomy"

\end_inset

, right), it seems natural to ask if there is actually a wave of proliferation
 that proceeds the differentiation.
 To dissect this behaviour, we used a transgenic fish which labels proliferating
 RPCs with destablized Green Fluorescent Protein (GFP) to literally visualise
 the proliferation wave (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-fucci"

\end_inset

).
 Counting the exact number of GFP-labelled cells in each half of saggital
 sections, we see that the behaviour of different locations only differ
 by their relative timing, whilst recapitulating (broadly) the same raise
 and fall of labelled cells.
 In particular, note that before the raise (understood to be the proliferation
 wave) the number of labelled cells is constant, implying that the progenitors
 are in a state of quiescence.
 This is consistent with previous results showing that between 15--24 hpf
 RPCs have extremely slow cell cycle times of about 40 hr on average (Li
 et al., 2000).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename zf-fucci.png
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:zf-fucci"

\end_inset


\series bold
Left
\series default
: Sagittal slices of a GFP-expressing retina at various time points (yellow
 arrow points to region of highest density of GFP and magenta arrow points
 to region of decline.
 
\series bold
Right
\series default
: Quantified GFP-positive cells over time by zone (nasal or temporal zone)
 and depth (the distance between the most peripheral section and the section
 of interests).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We thus have a picture of progenitors which are primed for action, waiting
 for a signal.
 Upon receiving that signal, they rapidly divide leading to a rise in number
 of progenitors.
 They then equally rapidly differentiate leading to a decrease in the GPF-label.
 The wave takes approximately 16 hours to progress from the central-most
 nasal side to the outermost temporal side, after which the only remaining
 progenitors reside in the CMZ.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stochastic progenitors, redux
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand what each progenitor is doing, we turn to clonal analysis.
 The experimental system is another transgenic line involving a cross between
 heat activated fluorescence (MAZe) and photoconvertable fluorescence (Kaede).
 In particular, heat shock (usually performed at 8 hpf) gives rise (with
 selection) to green fluorescent clones of one or two cells at 20 hpf in
 the retina, of which one cell will be chosen at some later time point (usually
 24, 32 or 48 hpf) to be photoconverted to red fluorescence by a UV laser.
 We thus have a choice of both induction time and also imaging time.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-clone-dists"

\end_inset

 shows some clone size distributions obtained, displaying the expected heterogen
eity of clone size, but also some novel features not seen before in the
 cultured system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename zf-clone-dists.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:zf-clone-dists"

\end_inset


\series bold
Left
\series default
: Size distributions of the clones induced at 24 hpf and recorded at 48
 hpf (left) or at 72 hpf (right), highlighting numbers of even (green) versus
 odd (blue) clones.
 
\series bold
Middle
\series default
: Size distributions of clones photoconverted at various times.
 The mean and SD are indicated.
 
\series bold
Right
\series default
: After photoconversion at 32 hpf, the size of the resulting subclone at
 72 hpf (y axis, depicted as the magenta cells in the schematic shown in
 inset) is, on average, approximately inversely correlated with the total
 size of the parent clone at 32 hpf (x axis, shown as the enclosed green
 and magenta cells in inset).
 The points show measurements from individual clones, while the mean and
 SEM are shown in purple.
 If the fate of RPCs is independent of clonally related cells, the average
 size of the subclone after photoconversion is predicted to vary as 
\begin_inset Formula $N/n$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 denotes the average total clone size at 72 hpf and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 denotes the average total clone size at 32 hpf.
 Indeed, the measured averages (purple) are broadly consistent with this
 prediction (orange line).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we note that there is a significant lack of odd sized clones from
 progenitors induced at 24 hpf and imaged at 48 hpf.
 This requires divisions in this time window to be predominantly symmetric
 renewal (PP) and sister RPCs should be synchronised --- a feature we had
 already seen in the cultured rat retinal progenitors; there it was not
 a particularly significant feature as PP divisions were rare.
 However, the lack of scarcity of 6-cell clones indicate that divisions
 are not synchronised beyond immediate sisters.
 Second, we see that this is no longer true of clones spanning 24 to 72
 hpf --- indicating asymmetric PD divisions becoming important.
 But if we look at the 48 to 72 hpf clones, we see that almost all divisions
 are terminal (DD), and furthermore with 4-cell clones greatly outnumbering
 3-cell clones, there is almost no PD either.
 Thus we conclude there being at least three separate phases: initially
 highly proliferative, composed of synchronised PP divisions, followed by
 a phase with significant PD divisions, finally almost entirely DD.
 Given such a complex and particular sequence, it is reasonable to ask if
 the progenitors are in fact stochastic at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To rule out the possibility that progenitors are pre-programmed at an early
 time (<20 hpf), but rather independently decide their fate, we study a
 slightly subtle aspect of the clone distribution.
 In particular, recall that our induction method actually creates clonally
 related green cells at an early time (and upon selection is this restricted
 to those of one or two cells in the retina at 20 hpf), but the subsequent
 photoconversion only affects one of that clone and turns it red.
 We thus look at the relation between the number of red cells at 72 hpf
 and the number of green cells at 32 hpf (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-clone-dists"

\end_inset

, right).
 We note that the average number of red cells falls as the inverse of the
 number of green cells, indicating that the RPCs index their behaviour by
 a lineage-internal measure rather than a tissue-wide signal.
 Furthermore, there is considerable variance --- if the size of a clone
 is pre-programmed, then there would be almost no variance, as later progenitors
 would know if they belonged to a small or large clone.
 Thus, we see that progenitors are still stochastic, but with evolving probabili
ties for chosing their fate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we will suppose that RPCs form a functionally equivalent, equipotent
 cell population with evolving proliferative potential, which is decoupled
 from the particular specification of individual cell types.
 Through temporal and spatial correlations, we expect to capture many aspects
 of the data, including correlations that might otherwise require a causative
 hypothesis.
 Any residual correlations between lineage and clone size are therefore
 a reflection of the histogenesis of cell types or a signature of early
 fate specification.
 In this paradigm, RPCs follow a (stochastic) developmental program, passing
 from a near-quiescent phase to an active proliferating phase and finally
 to a differentiating phase.
 The initiation and timing of this developmental program is defined by the
 wave of proliferation that sweeps around the retina, starting at the central
 nasal region and terminating at the peripheral temporal zone.
 In the following, we will use the timing of the first mitosis to define
 the start of the development program within each lineage.
 This occurs at around 23 hpf in the central nasal region, reaching the
 peripheral temporal region around 16 hours later.
 For simplicity, we therefore suppose that RPCs enter their active phase
 at a uniform rate, expecting that deviations from this will be beyond the
 resolution of the data.
 If we assume that, over the period from 24 to 48 hpf, RPCs are limited
 to the proliferative phase, measurements of the average clone size over
 this period suggest a cell cycle time of ca.
 6 hr, allowing approximately two rounds of symmetrical cell division.
 (Anticipating the results of the live-imaging study, our simulations are
 actually performed with a shifted gamma distribution, with a refractory
 period of 4 hr, mean of 6 hr, and width of 1 hr.) In addition, the lack
 of odd-sized clones requires a high degree of synchrony between division
 times of sister progenitors; we assume a difference between sister cell
 cycles of around 1 hr, normally distributed.
 Moreover, since the average clone size grows 12- to 13-fold over the period
 from 24 hpf to 72 hpf, we can deduce that each progenitor at 48 hpf must
 go on to produce, on average, three postmitotic cells.
 Thus, we may visualize a ‘‘typical’’ clone to consist of two rounds of
 symmetrical (PP-type) division, one round of asym- metrical (PD-type) division,
 and one round of terminal (DD-type) division leading to the average 12-fold
 increase in average clone size over the time course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the variability in size of clones at 72 hpf, induced at 24 hpf,
 provides a strong signature of stochasticity in cell fate choice.
 We therefore suppose that, within a lineage, the balance between proliferation
 and differentiation is achieved through stochastic fate decisions, with
 probabilities that vary through the developmental stages (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-model"

\end_inset

).
 For simplicity, we assume these changes to occur instantaneously, thus
 avoiding having to parameterize the change beyond just a single time.
 In particular, since clones induced at 48 hpf involve very few three-cell
 clones, PD divisions must be suppressed at these later times.
 Thus, there must be at least two such changes, to start and then stop PD
 divisions; we assume that there are only these two.
 Indeed, the proportion of four-cell to two-cell clones suggests that one
 in five cell divisions involves symmetrical self-renewal, while the remaining
 four divisions are terminal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 3de.pdf

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:zf-model"

\end_inset


\series bold
Upper
\series default
: The probabilities in the model for the second, third, and fourth mitosis
 within a lineage to occur, measured against the first mitosis.
 
\series bold
Lower
\series default
: The time-dependent probabilities for modes of division of RPCs in the
 model.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, to fully define the model, we only have to specify two time points
 to delineate the intermediate PD phase and the probabilities within that
 phase.
 The times were chosen to be 8 hr and 15 hr after the first mitosis, which
 essentially straddle the subsequent bursts of mitoses; it was found that
 the outcome was not particularly sensitive to the precise timing in any
 case, as long as they did not significantly reassign mitosis to be in different
 phases.
 The proportion of PP divisions was chosen, for simplicity again, to be
 the same as the terminal phase, i.e., one in five.
 The final parameter, the probability for PD divisions, was chosen to give
 the correct average size of 72 hpf clones induced at 24 hpf, which corresponded
 to two in five divisions.
 The proportion of DD is thus two in five during this intermediate phase.This
 model was implemented as a custom-written Monte Carlo simulation, which
 outputs probabilities for observing clones of different sizes.
 While a comparison of the measured clone size distribution to the model
 reveals a favorable fit to the experimental data (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-model-comparison"

\end_inset

), the freedom to adjust control parameters limits its credibility.
 Fortunately, we can make use of the live-imaging data to challenge some
 of the assumptions and predictions of the model, below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 3ghi.pdf

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:zf-model-comparison"

\end_inset

Shows fits between model predictions (cyan lines with shaded blue regions
 show 95% plausible intervals due to finite sampling) and size distributions
 (orange crosses) of clones induced at 24 hpf (left), 32 hpf (middle), and
 48 hpf (right).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Live Imaging of Clones and Histogenesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In limited cases, by time lapse imaging, it is possible to reconstruct the
 entire lineage tree (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-lineage-trees"

\end_inset

).
 Amazingly, almost all the features deduced from clonal can be observed,
 such as PP divisions following PD divisions, and the near synchronous sister
 divisions (fig).
 An unexpected feature is a variation of cell cycle length depending on
 fate outcome; in particular, PP and PD divisions are narrowly distributed
 around a similar average of 7.5 ± 1.3 hr, but terminal DD-type divisions
 have cell cycle times of 12.1 ± 1.0 hr.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename live-24h.pdf
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename live-image-trees.pdf
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:zf-lineage-trees"

\end_inset


\series bold
Upper: 
\series default
Reconstructed lineage trees from progenitors at 24 hpf, imaged at 48 hpf.
 Most cells have yet to differentiate, so whilst almost certainly progenitors,
 we cannot be certain.
 
\series bold
Lower
\series default
: Reconstructed lineage trees from 60 photoconverted progenitors at 32 hpf,
 imaged at 72 hpf.
 The numbers across the top indicate the rough spatial location of the progenito
r, nasal (1), middle (2) or temporal (3).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reconstructed lineage trees also offer an unprecedented view on how
 histogenesis occurs, i.e.
 how some cell types are born before others.
 At the population level, there is overlap leading to several cells types
 being generated at the same time (fig).
 We seek here to distinguish between simple overlap of strictly defined
 ordering within each lineage, and where ordering is loosely defined within
 individual lineage trees.
 We find that in DD divisions, almost all possible pairs of cell types occur
 (fig).
 This eliminates the possibility of stereotypical succession of cell types,
 however, it does not satisfactorily explain the observed histogenesis.
 To attempt an answer, we performed a qualitative analysis of the available
 data, by trying to compare the clone composition of sister RPCs.
 In particular, we compress each subclone from a tree into a string (represented
 graphically as a bitmap in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-barcode"

\end_inset

, left) and compare strings by a standard Levenshtein distance measure (which
 counts the number of single-character edits that would be necessary to
 turn one string into another).
 Finally, we use a standard hierarchical clustering algorithm to sort the
 strings according to their similarity.
 It was important to compare not only the final cell types generated by
 each lineage but also the structure and order in which the cells appear.
 To do this, we chose a particular representation of trees as strings in
 order to preserve the tree structure.
 Specifically, we embedded each tree into a complete tree of sufficient
 depth, then performed a depth-first traversal to gather the cell types
 into a string (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-barcode"

\end_inset

, left).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:zf-barcode"

\end_inset

, right, shows the subclones from the live-imaging data (with hierarchical
 similarity shown as a tree at the bottom and sister lineage relation at
 the top).
 We can discern no significant patterns from this data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

